answers.body_markdown:
Consider using a userscript instead - these run *automatically* when you visit a webpage that matches a pattern you define. [Tampermonkey](https://tampermonkey.net) is one of the most popular userscript managers. For example, the following script can remove the &quot;New User&quot; indicator on Stack Overflow sites:

```
// ==UserScript==
// @name         Hide New User
// @match        https://stackoverflow.com/*
// @grant        none
// ==/UserScript==

document.head.appendChild(document.createElement(&#39;style&#39;)).textContent = &quot;.new-contributor-indicator {display: none !important;}&quot;
```

You can also write a script that creates a button and adds a handler to the button which, when run, runs whatever other Javascript you want, on demand.

Try implementing a userscript, which basically is a computer program in your case a javascript program to modify a webpage.&lt;br&gt;
Userscripts are enabled by userscript manager browser extension.&lt;br&gt;
A popular chrome extension is [TamperMonkey][1].


  [1]: https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/tampermonkey/dhdgffkkebhmkfjojejmpbldmpobfkfo
